The title needs to be accurate and succinct (eg: <70 characters).

The replacement title will likely read:

logcat: -d, -t or -L, along with -f, do not set background cgroup

The body of the message describes why we are doing this, and can be as wordy as necessary to get the point across.

I said formerly ;-}, as in before this CL.

In the current code -f sets the global filename, and thus the whole process goes to background cgroup, batch scheduling and process priority regardless of which other flags are used.

The change is that if one uses any one or more of the -d, -t and -L flags in any combination, and also one specifies the -f flag, that we will _not_ go into the background cgroup (and thus _not_ cause a priority inversion).

